    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aa-l). <i>Carpobrotus </i>and <i>Mesembryanthemum </i>species are common on coastal dune systems and along bluffs throughout the section. They also occur along levees and dikes of the high marsh zone in the San Francisco Bay estuaries (Baye 2000, Baye et al. 2000), and along roadways in the outer coastal areas.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Aa-h, Aj-z). Stands occur in Suisun Marsh (Keeler-Wolf and Vaghti 2000) and in other areas of the Sacramento-San Joaquin River delta.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aa-m). Stands are common along dunes, bluffs, and similar exposed settings in the section. Removal of both <i>Carpobrotus </i>species to restore stands of the <i>Abronia latifolia-Ambrosia chamissonis </i>alliance has occurred for over two decades at the Eureka Dunes Protected Area, the Lanphere Dunes and the Ma-leâ€™l Dunes, the Manila Dunes, and the BLMâ€™s Samoa Dunes Recreation Area on the north spit of Humboldt Bay in Humboldt Co. Stands along Point Reyes National Seashore also contain both <i>Carpobrotus </i>species. They tend to replace dune mat plants of the <i>Abronia latifolia-Ambrosia chamissonis </i>and <i>Lupinus chamissonis-Ericameria ericoides</i> alliances. Park-funded ice plant removal projects are underway to remove large stands, primarily of <i>C. edulis </i>at several state beaches.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-j). Stands of <i>Carpobrotus edulis, Malephora crocea</i>,  and <i>Mesembryanthemum </i>spp. are common on coastal dune systems and along bluffs. Extensive plantings along roads invade and impact coastal scrub types. On coastal bluffs and terraces of San Diego Co., <i>C. chilensis </i>and other ice plants particularly invade <i>Artemisia californica </i>stands at urban-wildland interfaces (Evens and San 2005). At Vandenberg Air Force Base, <i>C. edulis </i>has invaded coastal grasslands, backdunes, and particularly coastal scrub (Dâ€™Antonio 1993, Underwood et al. 2002). In the northern Channel Islands, <i>M. crystallinum </i>competes with native coastal bluff and grassland stands (Johnson and Rodriguez 2001, Vivrette 1973). Johnson and Rodriguez (2001) sampled several stands dominated by <i>Malephora crocea.</i></li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba-p). <i>Mesembryanthemum nodiflorum </i>invades alkaline areas such as the San Jacinto River Valley in western Riverside Co. (Klein and Evens 2005), where it competes with natives such as <i>Atriplex coronata </i>var. <i>notatior </i>(a CNPS list 1B.1 plant).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> CalFire has recommended <i>Carpobrotus edulis </i>and other ice plant taxa as fire-resistant landscaping plants, because fire little affects plants due to their succulent habit. However, ice plants change coastal habitats in numerous ways, including alteration of soil chemistry and dune system geomorphology. In particular, salt buildup from ice plant leaves in soils effectively excludes native species from colonizing bare areas (Vivrette and Muller 1977). Dâ€™Antonio (1993) and Pickart and Sawyer (1998) reviewed methods of ice plant removal on coastal dunes, including suppression of growth and use of tractor-tread bobcats. </div>
</div>

    

    

